**Hi, welcome to Stack Overflow and JavaScript as well!
It&#39;s unclear how much experience you have with JavaScript and HTML, so here are a number of options:**

The best way to get started is following an online tutorial or book to learn and practise new skills. Websites like https://www.w3schools.com/js/js_htmldom_html.asp and https://www.digitalocean.com/community/tutorials/introduction-to-the-dom may be a good place to start for you.

----------

If you do know a fair bit of HTML and JS already, but aren&#39;t sure how to link them together, here are some of the basics:

The JS `document` object contains a huge number of methods and properties to allow you to interact with the webpage, or the document. When you create an HTML file, like the one below, you can set IDs and classnames for the elements on the page - these are essentially like names to help you interact with these elements.

Here&#39;s a very basic HTML file:

    &lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
    &lt;html&gt;
    &lt;head&gt;
      &lt;title&gt;An HTML webpage&lt;/title&gt;
      &lt;meta charset=&quot;UTF-8&quot;&gt;
    &lt;/head&gt;
    &lt;body&gt;
    
    &lt;h1 id=&quot;header&quot; class=&quot;text&quot;&gt;This is my webpage&lt;/h1&gt;
    &lt;p id=&quot;body&quot; class=&quot;text&quot;&gt;This is the body text of my webpage!&lt;/p&gt;
    
    &lt;/body&gt;
    &lt;/html&gt;

You can see that we&#39;ve given the h1 element, a header, the id &quot;header&quot; and the class &quot;text&quot;. No two elements can share the same id but they can share classes. This is useful because you can group all the text elements on the page together, for example.

Now, if we wanted to use JavaScript to edit the header text of the page, we could do this:

    document.getElementById(&quot;header&quot;).innerHTML = &quot;A new header&quot;;

We could also do this:

    document.getElementsByTagName(&quot;h1&quot;)[0].innerHTML = &quot;A new header&quot;;

Note: the above JS will get **every** h1 element on the page, so we need to add `[0]` to only get the first one

If you want to change the colour of the body text, you could do this:

    document.getElementById(&quot;body&quot;).color = &quot;blue&quot;;

Now this is a very limited view of what you can do with DOM modification, but hopefully it will serve as a good starting point. I would recommened checking out the websites above.

*If this answer has helped you, please click the tick/checkmark on the left to mark it as correct - thank you!*

